name: Congresswoman Julia Brownley
tweet_text: The Six Triple-Eight was the largest black women‚Äôs unit deployed in World War II, and only received formal recognition for their service decades after the war ended.

name: Congresswoman Julia Brownley
tweet_text: Even when facing harsh weather and constant scrutiny from supervisors, the battalion worked around to clock and soon became the most productive mail service throughout Europe. The unit was allotted six months to complete their mission. The Six Triple Eight did it in three.

name: Congresswoman Julia Brownley
tweet_text: Adams developed an incredible system that allowed the unit to sort and deliver the backlog of over 17 million pieces of mail. The servicewomen worked 24 hours a day, seven days a week, and in three rotating eight-hour shifts. Each shift sorted and processed 65,000 pieces of mail.

name: Congresswoman Julia Brownley
tweet_text: In response, the Women‚Äôs Army Corps formed the all-black Six Triple Eight (6888) Battalion to deliver millions of pieces of mail and restore high spirits to troops across Europe.

name: Congresswoman Julia Brownley
tweet_text: In the height of World War II, oversees military personnel faced a serious problem: due to a six-month backlog of mail, soldiers were not receive letters or packages from loved ones, which plummeted morale.
